body:
Yes.

> If yes, do I have the option (through the Python API) to disable telemetry ?

Please 

1. Build onnxruntime from source by yourself. 

Normally when onnxruntime was built from source, the cmake option ['onnxruntime_USE_TELEMETRY'](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L92) is default off, and the "ENABLE_TELEMETRY" C macro isn't defined anywhere.  In such a case Microsoft won't collect your data. Our official binaries are built in a special way that has some special extra steps to enable the two things. 

2. You may also consider to disable [Windows Error Reporting service](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Error_Reporting) if you have concern.  

The service is mainly for error reporting. It only uploads data to Microsoft when your program doesn't behave well(like: crash). 

You may disable the service by setting the following registry value to 1.
```
[HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\Windows Error Reporting]
"Disabled"=dword:00000001
```
@faxu  - Maybe the privacy policy can be part of the FAQ ?

Thank you for the answer, I understood telemetry was disabled using custom builds, but my question was about the official package (which is what most people will use and is the easiest way to distribute cross-platform without having to maintain everything yourself).

_Using official packages from the Python API_, if a window user disables  the _Windows Error Reporting service_, will onnxruntime still send telemetry data ?

What about Mac & Linux ? When telemetry will be enabled there on the official builds (if that's not already the case), will there be a way to disable telemetry ?

Would you be open to add a function in the (Python) API to let anyone freely choose whereas or not to enable telemetry in the official build ?

> Using official packages from the Python API, if a window user disables the Windows Error Reporting service, will onnxruntime still send telemetry data ?

Yes.

> What about Mac & Linux ? When telemetry will be enabled there on the official builds 

No.
Please reopen it if you have more questions.
I'm so sorry. I think I was wrong. The official python package doesn't have telemetry. The nuget one has.

Thank you for the answer

> > Using official packages from the Python API, if a window user disables the Windows Error Reporting service, will onnxruntime still send telemetry data ?

It would be nice to let people choose whereas they want to send telemetry. Telemetry already lead to VSCode vs. VSCodium. It would be a shame we'd have to maintain a telemetry free "onnxruntium" build in parrallel.

That's really great, thanks for the precision. maybe it could be precised in the Privacy policy which packages contain telemetry and which don't

issue.body:
**Description**: Currently, official ORT packages for Windows (using TraceLogging) are configured to collect telemetry. The C API exposes knobs to disable this but C# and Python do not. This change addresses that.

**Motivation and Context**
1) Minimize gap between C#/Python and the C APIs
2) Account for user request in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3898 (`do I have the option (through the Python API) to disable telemetry`)
